data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Works | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Wakes `WaitOne` | Still works, but not idiomatic |
| Manual signal + lock + Queue | Functional | Replace with `Channel<T>` |

### Bug in Original Code

**Race condition**: Multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne()` returning and `Reset()` will coalesce into a single signal — only one item gets dequeued, the rest are silently stuck.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _runTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _runTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();                         // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try { await _runTask; }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Key Migration Decisions

**1. `Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue`**
- Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, zero-lock fast path
- `ReadAllAsync` drains all items — fixes the original race condition

**2. `CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort/Interrupt`**
- Cooperative cancellation is the only supported pattern in .NET 5+
- Two-phase shutdown: `Writer.Complete()` for graceful drain, then `CancelAfter` as hard stop

**3. `Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`**
- Uses the ThreadPool; avoids orphaned thread lifetime issues
- Returns a `Task` you can `await` for clean shutdown

### If `Handle()` is async

Replace the loop body directly — no wrapper needed:

```csharp
await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
{
    await HandleAsync(item, ct);
}
```

### If you need bounded backpressure

```csharp
// Slow producers when 1000 items are buffered
Channel.CreateBounded<string>(new BoundedChannelOptions(1000)
{
    FullMode = BoundedChannelFullMode.Wait
});
// Then use: await _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item);
```

### Common Pitfall: "I'll just remove `Abort` and keep the rest"

This half-migration is tempting but fragile — `Thread.Interrupt` only interrupts managed blocking calls (`WaitOne`, `Sleep`), not arbitrary user code in `Handle()`. If `Handle()` hangs, you have no timeout. The `CancellationToken` pattern propagates cancellation into any async I/O your handler does.
